# No tracker or spec-checklist noise in source

## Issue and ticket IDs

- **Never** put tracker references in application code: no `WALLET-105`, `REF-001`, `GH-123`, Jira keys, or similar in:
  - comments and docblocks
  - string literals (including user-visible copy)
  - inline `//` / `/* */` next to implementations
- Describe behavior in plain language only (e.g. “focus trap; restore focus on close”).

## Spec sections and “executable checklist” references

- **Never** use comments or docblocks to tie code to internal write-ups: no **§** section markers (`§7`, `§8.3`, `§7–8.3`), no checklist-style breadcrumbs (`8.3`, “executable checklist”, “ModPol §…”, “see TECH_SPEC §…”), and no pointers that mean “we implemented backlog row _n_”.
- Comments stay **minimal** and explain **what this code does** (and non-obvious **why** in one phrase if needed). Rationale, numbering, and cross-links belong in **`docs/`** and **`ai-docs/`**, not next to implementations.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
/** Unified feed (ModPol §7–8.3). */

// ✅ GOOD
/** Unified dashboard proposal feed; vote and eligibility wiring stay per-tool. */
```

## Where longer design references live

- Use **tracked design docs** under `docs/` (and internal specs under `ai-docs/` where appropriate). Keep internal checklists and scratch execution notes **out of** `src/`, `src-tauri/`, scripts, and shipped config; optional private doc trees must not be the only home for anything reviewers must follow.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
/** Modal focus trap (see WALLET-105). */

// ✅ GOOD
/** Modal: focus trap and restore previous focus on close. */
```
